{Nybäck- Neiskans, rapid. Involves Carlsbad pawn structure} 1. d4 Nf6 {fits for
positional play} 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 (3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6
{typical Carlsbad, white can play Nf3, or Bd3 Ne2 f3 e4. In game. Main game
has difference as Night is already forced to f3, while black has a6 weakness} )
3... a6 {avoids Catalan} 4. Nc3 (4. g3 b5 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bg2 c5 {gives black
dream setup} ) 4... d5 {99% of players take on c5, claiming that a6 was waste
of time; otherwise black takes and plays b5 support} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Qb3 Be7
{to avoid known/previously played lines. after 34, just take and castle}  (6...
c6 7. e4 Nxe4 (7... dxe4 8. Ng5 {and Bc4 gives deadly initative} ) 8. Nxe4 Qe7
{important intermezzo move} 9. Bd2 Qxe4+ (9... dxe4 10. O-O-O exf3 11. Re1 Be6
12. Bc4 fxg2 13. Rhg1 Kd8 {black survives} 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Rxe6 Qd7 16. Rge1
{but difficult in fast time controls} ) 10. Kd1 Qe7 11. Bd3 Qd8 12. Re1+ Be7
13. Bb4 Be6 14. Bf5 Bxb4 15. Qxb4 Qe7 16. Qxe7+ Kxe7 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Ng5
{equal drawish game} ) 7. Bg5 {must be played before e3, to be true Carlsbad} 
7... c6 {to support pawn} 8. e3 {typically white attacks queenside and black in
kingside. If white can exchange a&b pawns, c6 is weakness} 8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 O-O
10. O-O Re8 11. Rac1 Nf8 {hard to evaluate best alternative in short time
control, Nf8 is typical idea in these positions}  (11... Nh5 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13.
Rfe1 Ndf6 14. Na4 g6 15. Ne5 Ng7 16. f3 {white is still pushing,trying for e4
on Nc5} 16... Bf5)  (11... h6 12. Bf4 {h3 Bh2 avoids bishop trade} )  (11...
Ne4 {only possible as queen is not on c2} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Nd2
{unsure, if a6 push actually matters} 14... Nf6 15. Qa3 Qxa3 16. bxa3 {a5, a4
Na4 gives white clear advantage as black has no counterplay} ) 12. Na4 Ne6 13.
Bh4 Ne4 {probably should have been played earlier} 14. Bxe7 Rxe7 15. Nb6
{inaccuracy}  (15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Nd2 Ng5 17. Qb6 {white keeps better position} 
17... Qd6 18. Nc4 {Qg6 would be promising attack for black, but back rank
suffers} ) 15... Rb8 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Ne5 {white has f3 & d5 ideas} 17... Nc7
{Be6, f6 and white loses momentum} 18. Nxc8 (18. Rxc6 Rxe5 (18... bxc6 19. Nxc6
Qd6 20. Nxb8 {wont really work for black} ) 19. Rxc7 Qxc7 20. dxe5 Be6 21. Qb4
Qxe5 {gives black some change to play for a win with h5,h4,h3} ) 18... Qxc8
{rook can't take as Qb7 is a problem} 19. f3 exf3 20. Rxf3 Nd5 {makes more
sense visually}  (20... Qe6 {can't be played to get rid of f7 pin} 21. Nxc6
Qxb3 22. Nxe7+ {intermezzo check, resignable} )  (20... Ne6 21. d5 Ng5 {is
difficult to evaluate over the board} ) 21. e4 (21. Rxf7 Rxf7 22. Nxf7 Kxf7 23.
e4 Qg4 {black is not in trouble} 24. exd5 (24. Rf1+ Kg8 25. exd5 Qxd4+ {black
is up a pawn} ) 24... Qxd4+) 21... Nf6 {Qe6 next move would equalize for black}
22. Rxf6 {looks like panic move} 22... gxf6 23. Qg3+ Kh8 {corner is usually
better as it allows attack from one side only} 24. Ng4 (24. Qh4 fxe5 25. Qxe7
Qe6 26. Qxe6 fxe6 27. dxe5 Rd8 28. Rc2 {white is slightly better because of
double extra pawn} ) 24... Qc7 (24... Qd8 {only good move} 25. Nxf6 (25. Rd1
Rxe4 {can give exchange back and reach drawish endgame} 26. Nh6 Qf8 27. Nxf7+
Qxf7 28. Qxb8+ Kg7) 25... Qxd4+)  (24... Rxe4 {problem is that b8 rook is
always under attack} 25. Nxf6 Rxd4 26. Qe5 Qd8 {is looking really bad} 27. Nd7+
) 25. Qf2 (25. Qh4 Qf4 26. Qxf6+ Qxf6 27. Nxf6 Rd8 {black is not worse and has
a change to play for victory} ) 25... Qd6 26. Nxf6 {starts to look wrong for
black} 26... Rd8 27. d5 Kg7 28. Rf1 cxd5 29. Qh4 (29. exd5 {allows queen trade
idea} 29... Qe5 {with Qe3} ) 29... h6 30. Qg4+ Kh8 31. Qf5 {unstoppable mate} *

